Hi,

This is a response to an email as to whether a
negative pre-factor covers up the fact that a
reversible reaction is written in the reverse
direction: C = A + B.  I think the answer is no, since
there is physically no concept of negative pre-factor.

When the reaction is written in the regular way, for
example: A + B = C, the rate of reaction will be: r =
kf * A * B - kr* C.

If the reaction is written in the reverse direction,
the rate of reaction would be r = kr* C - kf* A * B.
Then, the pre-exponential factor for the forward
reaction will be kr which will still be positive.

Again following microscopic reversibility, the kf = kr
/ Keq_reverse, where Keq_reverse = 1/Keq.

- Bharath

